\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 1: Distributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In class, we only looked explicitly at 1d distributions, but a distribution
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{d}$
\end_inset

 can obviously be defined similarly, as (continuous linear) maps 
\begin_inset Formula $f\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

 from smooth (infinitely differentiable) localized (compact supoport) functions
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 to numbers.
 Analogous to class, define the distributional gradient 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla f$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla f\{\phi\}=f\{-\nabla\phi\}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the vector whose components are 
\begin_inset Formula $f\{-\partial\phi/\partial x_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\ldots,d$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

