\end_inset

 Define a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

surface delta function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(\partial V)\{\phi\}=\oint_{\partial V}\phi(\vec{x})d^{d-1}\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 to give the surface integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\oint_{\partial V}$
\end_inset

 of the test function.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Suppose we have a regular distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $f\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

 defined by the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\vec{x})=\begin{cases}
f_{1}(\vec{x}) & \vec{x}\in V\\
f_{2}(\vec{x}) & \vec{x}\notin V
\end{cases}$
\end_inset

, where we may have a discontinuity 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}-f_{1}\neq0$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial V$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that the distributional gradient of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla f=\delta(\partial V)\left[f_{2}(\vec{x})-f_{1}(\vec{x})\right]\vec{n}(\vec{x})+\begin{cases}
\nabla f_{1}(\vec{x}) & \vec{x}\in V\\
\nabla f_{2}(\vec{x}) & \vec{x}\notin V
\end{cases},
\]

\end_inset

where the second term is a regular distribution given by the ordinary 18.02
 gradient of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 (assumed to be differentiable), while the first term is the singular distributi
on 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta(\partial V)\left[f_{1}(\vec{x})-f_{2}(\vec{x})\right]\vec{n}(\vec{x})\{\phi\}=\oint_{\partial V}\left[f_{1}(\vec{x})-f_{2}(\vec{x})\right]\vec{n}(\vec{x})\phi(\vec{x})d^{d-1}\vec{x}.
\]

\end_inset

 You can use the integral identity that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{V}\nabla\psi d^{d}\vec{x}=\oint_{\partial V}\psi\vec{n}d^{d-1}\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 to help you integrate by parts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}f\{\phi\}=f\{\nabla^{2}\phi\}$
\end_inset

, derive a similar expression to the above for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}f$
\end_inset

.
 Note that you should have one term from the discontinuity 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}-f_{2}$
\end_inset

, and another term from the discontinuity 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla f_{1}-\nabla f_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 (Recall how we integrated 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}$
\end_inset

 by parts in class some time ago.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 2: Green's functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider Green's functions of the self-adjoint indefinite operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}=-\nabla^{2}-\omega^{2}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa>0$
\end_inset

) over all space (
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 in 3d), with solutions that 
\begin_inset Formula $\to0$
\end_inset

 at infinity.
 (This is related to the previous problem.) As in class, thanks to the translatio
nal and rotational invariance of this problem, we can find 
\begin_inset Formula $G(\vec{x},\vec{x}')=g(|\vec{x}-\vec{x}'|)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $g(r)$
\end_inset

 in spherical coordinates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $g(r)$
\end_inset

 in 3d, similar to the procedure in class.
\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Similar to the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}=-\nabla^{2}$
\end_inset

 in class, first solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $g(r)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

, and write 
\begin_inset Formula $g(r)=\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{+}}f_{\epsilon}(r)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\epsilon}(r)=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $r\leq\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 [Hint: although Wikipedia writes the spherical 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}g(r)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{r^{2}}(r^{2}g')'$
\end_inset

, it may be more convenient to write it equivalently as 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}g=\frac{1}{r}(rg)''$
\end_inset

, as in class, and to solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $h(r)=rg(r)$
\end_inset

 first.
 Hint: if you get sines and cosines from this differential equation, it
 will probably be easier to use complex exponentials, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\omega r}$
\end_inset

, instead.] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In the previous part, you should find two solutions, both of which go to
 zero at infinity.
 To choose between them, remember that this operator arose from a 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-i\omega t}$
\end_inset

 time dependence.
 Plug in this time dependence and impose an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

outgoing wave
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 boundary condition (also called a Sommerfield or radiation boundary condition):
 require that waves be traveling 
\emph on
outward
\emph default
 far away, not 
\emph on
inward
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Then, evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}g=\delta(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 in the distributional sense: 
\begin_inset Formula $(\hat{A}g)\{q\}=g\{\hat{A}q\}=q(0)$
\end_inset

 for an arbitrary (smooth, localized) test function 
\begin_inset Formula $q(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 to solve for the unknown constants in 
\begin_inset Formula $g(r)$
\end_inset

.
 [Hint: when evaluating 
\begin_inset Formula $g\{\hat{A}q\}$
\end_inset

, you may need to integrate by parts on the radial-derivative term of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}q$
\end_inset

; don't forget the boundary term(s).]
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Check that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\to0^{+}$
\end_inset

 limit gives the answer from class for the Green's function of 
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

